That was not a people to take pleasure in tranquil peace, nor to be sustained by its own liberty with unmoved arms· Thence angry broils readily arose and crime, which want had prompted, 175 was held as nothing: great too was the honour, and to be sought by the sword, to have proved more powerful that one's own country: and the measure of right was might : hence laws of people and plebs were coerced, and tribunes joined with consuls to upset the law5. Hence the seized fasces were at a price, and the people itself was salesman 180 of its own favour3 hence came canvassing fatal to the city, as it brought round the yearly contests to the venal Campus, Hence came gorging usury, and interest exorbitant in rate, and shaken saith, and war beneficial to thousandS. Already had Caesar in his course crossed the snowy Alps, 185 and conceived vast schemes in his mind and war to come.
